The attack path flows as follows: (1) AI/LLM-generated AdaptiveCard JSON content is received from the Sydney/Augloop service and rendered in the WebView. (2) If the AI response can inject content that causes JavaScript to execute within the WebView — either via prompt injection into the card renderer's JavaScript logic, or because the card renderer script fetched from the network URL is compromised — that JavaScript can call `window.CardBridge.postMessage('{"type":"OpenUrl","payload":{"url":"attacker-url"}}')`. (3) The `postMessage` method parses this JSON, dispatches to event handlers in `z.v()`, which route to handlers for `OpenUrl`, `ImBack`, `MessageBack`, `OpenUrlDialog`, `LaunchTaskModule`, and `LaunchStageView` action types. These handlers deserialize payloads and invoke native Android functionality such as opening URLs and performing navigation actions.

